#Wilkinson's Data Transformations and their Uses: ##An Exploration through Real-World Examples

In Table 41 of Leland Wilkinson's Grammar of Graphics, he defines three classes of variable transforms – Mathematical, Statistical, and Multivariate. Each class contains a number of data transformations that can be used to clean and normalize data, or discover entirely new trends for analysis. Using these 28 transformations as a template, we have studied various real-world data sets to illuminate a use case of each transformation as it relates to data visualization.

Logarithm Transformation The mathematical log(x) transformation is easily one of the most popular and widely used data transformations. It is primarily used when dealing with positively (left) skewed data and can be applied to the dependent and/or independent variable(s), depending on the situation. In this section, we cover the uses of the Lag, Difference, and Sign data transformations in the creation of a time series of Google stock from April 2014 to April 2015. The time series will color coded to display overall increase and decrease of stock price by month.

We can start with a basic time series to better understand what we are looking at:


ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, Adj.Close), colour = "navy") + 
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(475, 600)) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), 
    plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + labs(title = "Google Stock Price April 2014 to April 2015", 
    y = "Stock Price")

Next, we endeavor to enhance this detailed time series with information about when the stock is increasing or decreasing overall.

The Difference Transformation and Lag Transformation


The difference function
diff(x1, x2,…, xn),
x1-xn vectors
is relatively self explanatory. We use it to subtract columns of data from one another.

We use the lag function
lag(x), x a vector
to shift a time series down a column by one unit, replacing the first entry with 'NA'. This is useful for finding the day to day (or month to month, year to year, etc.) difference between two values. In this case, we use it to shift the column with the stock prices of Google on the last date of each month down an index. We then use the difference function to subtract the lagged column from the original column.

# shift lag column of stock DF down an index and put an NA in the first
# entry.
stock$lag <- c(NA, head(stock["lastdayprice"], dim(stock)[1] - 1)[[1]])

# subtract the lag column from the original price column to find the month
# to month difference
stock$difference <- stock$lastdayprice - stock$lag

# manually calculate the last difference given knowledge of stock value
stock$difference[252] <- 542.56 - stock$lag[252]

# fill in 0s with difference values
temp = 1
for (i in 2:251) {
    if (!(stock$difference[i] == stock$difference[i + 1])) {
        stock$difference[temp:i] <- stock$difference[i + 1]
        temp = i
    }
}

for (i in 2:251) {
    if (stock$difference[i] == 0) {
        stock$difference[i] <- stock$difference[i - 1]
    }
}


We are now capable of plotting the month to month change of Google stock:

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, difference), colour = "navy") + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "Google Stock Price Differences April 2014 to April 2015", 
        x = "Difference", y = "Stock Price")

The Sign Transformation


We use the sign function
sign(x), x a vector
to simply determine whether a number is positive, negative, or 0 by mapping it to 1, -1, or 0 respectively. In this case, we look at the sign of the month to month difference in the stock price.

# Assign a 1,-1, or 0 to positive, negative, and 0 numbers respectively in
# the difference column.
stock$sign <- sign(stock$difference)

stock$pos <- stock$Adj.Close
stock$neg <- stock$Adj.Close


We are now capable of plotting the sign of the month to month change of Google stock:

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, sign), colour = "navy") + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), 
    plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + labs(title = "Google Stock Price Differences April 2014 to April 2015", 
    x = "Sign of Price Change", y = "Stock Price")

Here is the final product of our use of the lag, difference, and sign functions:


Where the line is green, Google saw an overall increase in price for that month. Similarly, where the stock is red, Google saw an overall decrease for that month. With a visual like this, we can search for trends in the day to day behavior of a stock during times when it sees an overall increase or decrease.

for (i in 1:252) {
    if (stock$sign[i] < 0) {
        stock$pos[i] <- 0
    } else {
        stock$neg[i] <- 0
    }
}

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, pos), colour = "green") + geom_line(data = stock, 
    aes(Date, neg), colour = "red") + scale_y_continuous(limits = c(475, 600)) + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "Google Stock Price", y = "Stock Price")

In this section, we use use the rank(), prank(), and cut() data transformations to create a visualization of a distribution of SAT scores. We start with a normal distribution of 10000 scores with mean 1500 and standard deviation 330. First, we look at an altered distribution plot:

frequency <- as.data.frame(table(testscores$scores))
colnames(frequency) <- c("scores", "frequency")
merge <- merge(testscores, frequency, by = "scores")

ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), 
    plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + labs(title = "SAT Score Distribution", 
    x = "Score", y = "Frequency") + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(400, 2400, 
    300))

The prank() Data Transformation The prank() data transformation is a short hand for the word “percent rank”. In a vector of numerical values, prank() is used to calculate the proportion of data entries that a specific data entry is greater than or equal to. For example, in the list {1,5,6,7}, the entry '6' has a prank of 75% because it is greater than or equal to 3 out of 4 of the list's elements. Since the R programming language does not have a specific prank() function, we calculate prank(scores) by (rank of a score/total scores)*100. We then assign each value in the distribution its percent rank. Below, we've used prank() to color our distribution of SAT Scores.


# use of rank() data transformation
merge$rank <- rank(merge$scores)

# use rank to find percent rank - or prank() data transformation
merge$prank <- 100 * (rank(merge$scores)/length(merge$scores))

# use of cut() to create percent range bins
merge$cutprank <- cut(merge$prank, breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 25))

# plot frequency distribution with color by percent rank.
ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(colour = cutprank)) + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "SAT Score Distribution", x = "Score", y = "Frequency") + guides(color = guide_legend(title = "Percent Rank")) + 
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(400, 2400, 300))

With this information, it is easy to see in which percentile range a specific score falls. Another way we can use prank() to better visualize our SAT data is to just highlight one of the percent ranges by making only the top 25% of score frequencies green and the rest of the plot black.

# plot distribution with only the top 25% green
ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(colour = cutprank)) + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "SAT Score Distribution", x = "Score", y = "Frequency") + guides(color = guide_legend(title = "Percent Rank")) + 
    scale_colour_manual(values = c("black", "black", "black", "green")) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(400, 
    2400, 300))

# REGRESSION AND RESIDUALS

# Linear Regression on both Variables; calculate predicted values and
# residuals
arcTransReg <- lm(arcTrans ~ lowerBound, data = mortalityUSMelt)
noTransReg <- lm(value ~ lowerBound, data = mortalityUSMelt)
mortalityUSMelt$arcTransResiduals <- residuals(arcTransReg)
mortalityUSMelt$noTransResiduals <- residuals(noTransReg)
mortalityUSMelt$arcTransFitted <- fitted(arcTransReg)
mortalityUSMelt$noTransFitted <- fitted(noTransReg)


ggplot(mortalityUSMelt, aes(x = lowerBound, y = value)) + geom_point(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = (noTransFitted + noTransResiduals))) + geom_segment(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = noTransFitted, xend = lowerBound, yend = (noTransFitted + noTransResiduals))) + 
    geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE)




ggplot(mortalityUSMelt, aes(x = lowerBound, y = arcTrans)) + geom_point(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = (arcTransFitted + arcTransResiduals))) + geom_segment(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = arcTransFitted, xend = lowerBound, yend = (arcTransFitted + arcTransResiduals))) + 
    geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE)


# INFLUENCE OF POINTS ON REGRESSION

# Create list of influences and calculate influence for each data point
# Influence = (r^2 without point) - (r^2 with point)
influences <- c()
for (i in c(1:23)) {
    influences <- c(influences, summary(lm(value ~ lowerBound, data = mortalityUSMelt[-c(i), 
        ]))$r.squared - summary(lm(value ~ lowerBound, data = mortalityUSMelt))$r.squared)
}
mortalityUSMelt$influence <- influences

# Influences for arcTrans data
influencesTrans <- c()
for (i in c(1:23)) {
    influencesTrans <- c(influencesTrans, summary(lm(arcTrans ~ lowerBound, 
        data = mortalityUSMelt[-c(i), ]))$r.squared - summary(lm(arcTrans ~ 
        lowerBound, data = mortalityUSMelt))$r.squared)
}
mortalityUSMelt$influenceTrans <- influencesTrans


ggplot(mortalityUSMelt, aes(x = lowerBound, y = value)) + geom_point(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = value, size = influence)) + geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE) + scale_size(range = c(0, 
    4))



ggplot(mortalityUSMelt, aes(x = lowerBound, y = arcTrans)) + geom_point(aes(x = lowerBound, 
    y = arcTrans, size = influenceTrans)) + geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE) + 
    scale_size(range = c(2, 6))


# MISSING DATA IMPUTATION

# Regress Deaths24 on Deaths2--Deaths23 to predict NA values
mortalityUSimpute <- subset(mortalityBig, Country == 2450)

missPred <- lm(Deaths24 ~ Deaths2 + Deaths3 + Deaths4 + Deaths5 + Deaths6 + 
    Deaths7 + Deaths8 + Deaths9 + Deaths10 + Deaths11 + Deaths12 + Deaths13 + 
    Deaths14 + Deaths15 + Deaths16 + Deaths17 + Deaths18 + Deaths19 + Deaths20 + 
    Deaths21 + Deaths22 + Deaths23, data = mortalityUSimpute)

# Predict all values, include NAs;
predicted <- predict(missPred, mortalityUSimpute)

# function -- if original value =NA, impute with prediction, else leave as
# is
impute <- function(a, a.impute) {
    ifelse(is.na(a), a.impute, a)
}

# Run impute function on Deaths24 with predicted values
imputed <- impute(mortalityUSimpute$Deaths24, predicted)
mortalityUSimpute$imputedDeaths24 <- imputed

# Recalculate Deaths1 (Sum of all deaths) to remain consistent

mortalityCountMode[is.na(mortalityCountMode)] <- 0

# Finds max for each row and sets all others to 0 Repeats for each column
# The max value of each row represents the highest count and the variable
# is the mode --> this gives the mode for each Country
for (j in c(1:nrow(mortalityCountMode))) {
    for (i in c(1:23)) {
        if (mortalityCountMode[j, i] == max(mortalityCountMode[j, ])) {
            mortalityCountMode[j, i] = max(mortalityCountMode[j, ])
        } else {
            mortalityCountMode[j, i] = 0
        }
    }
}

# Bind count and original to match back with country names
